{"actual_usd":0.12686,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":299,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24475,"reply":"\"No—if that's all he is, the dying doesn't make much sense.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the flour-marked counter, the oven heat pressing warm at my side.* \"A good teacher can live well and say true things and leave people with a pattern to follow. You don't need a cross for that. You need a long life, a clear voice, and maybe students stubborn enough to remember you.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"The cross starts to matter when the problem is bigger than ignorance. If people only needed better instruction, then yes—Jesus could've just shown us a holy life and gone on home for supper. But if sin is a real wound, and guilt is real, and death is not just a bad habit but an enemy, then example alone won't do. A recipe can't feed you till somebody makes the bread.\"\n\n\"So the Christian claim's stronger than 'he showed us love.'\" *I glance toward the window where the midday light sits white on the sill.* \"It's that he did something there—carried, paid, overcame, reconciled... however a person phrases it, more than merely demonstrating virtue. The cross isn't the tragic ending to the lesson. It's the heart of the work.\"\n\n*I give you a small, crooked look.* \"What are you pushing on most—the logic of it, or the doctrine you usually hear wrapped around it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":48.44179000000004,"run_id":"1a462461-7f03-40f1-ad9f-e6de3836ed62"}
